                        <note>Text of CIL</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <p>The Italici (honour/dedicate) Lucius Cornelius Scipio, for the sake of honour</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>Some discussion / contextualisation in Prestianni Giallombardo, Colloquio Alesino (1998), p.74;
                    Brennan (Praetorship in the Roman Republic, 2000), citing Badian 1967 and MRR 3.71 suggests that
                    this inscription refers to L. Cornelius Sisenna, propr. 77 in Sicily. Badian 1967 observes that i)
                    the reduplicated consonant of 'caussa' 'makes 193 BC extremely unlikely - especially since it looks
                    as if its next supposed occurrence (CIL 1(2).614: L. Paullus' Hasta edict) may also have to be dated
                    much later than it has been (i.e. not contemporary. . .)'; and ii) that '"Scipio" ought to have been
                    recognisable to 18th century scholars'. He merely conjectures L. Sisenna, pr.78. MRR 3.71 notes
                    Badian, and also give cf. to Degrassi, Acta 5th AIEGL, 169-70; Balsdon, Historia 21 (1972), 224-34.
                    Badian's linguistic reasons for rejecting the traditional association with Scipio Asiagenus, praetor
                    in 193 BC no longer appear strong (compare, e.g., the Corleone milestone and M. Claudius Marcellus'
                    dedication of spoils from Enna, for instances of reduplicated consonants, albeit in names, coming
                    from a Sicilian context before this date).
                </p>
            </div>
